of expression and representation, this volume focuses on postwar German and Austrian writers who made use of music in their exploration of the National Socialist past. Their works invoke, however, new questions: What happens when we cross the line between narration and documentation, and between memory and a musical piece? How does identification and fascination affect our reading of the text? What kind of ethical issues do these testimonies raise? As this volume shows, reading these musical biographies is both troubling and compelling since they ‘fail’ to come to terms with the past. In playing the haunting music that does not let us put the matter to rest, they call into question not only the exclusion of personal stories by official narratives, but also challenge writers’ and readers’ most intimate perspectives on an unmasterable past.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGerman fictionxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aGerman fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMemory in literature. 0aMusic and literaturexHistoryx20th centuryxAustria. 0aMusic and literaturexHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aMusic and literaturezAustriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMusic and literaturezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMusic in literaturexAustriaxGermanyxCriticism, interpretation, etcxHistory. 0aMusic in literature. 4aErzählwissenschaft. 4aHolocaust. 4aKultur / Deutschland. 4aMusikalische Poetik. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aGerman culture.  aHolocaust.  aMusical Poetics.  anarrative.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2016 Part 1z978311076250108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z